        return hint ? `- ${t} (${n}): ${hint}` : `- ${t} (${n})`;
      })
      .join("\n");

    const headerNote =
      source === "shard"
        ? `${older.length} older facts (plus any newer ones), sharded at facts_Topic/${opts.userId}/`
        : `${older.length} older facts grouped by topic`;

    block +=
      `[Memory topics — ${headerNote}]\n` +
      indexLines +
      "\n\n" +
      "If the user asks about a topic above and the recent facts don't cover it,\n" +
      "call the `list_facts` MCP tool with the topic name — the server reads\n" +
      "that shard file directly, e.g. `list_facts({ query: \"bridge-token\" })`.\n" +
      "Use query=\"\" and tail=0 only if you genuinely need the full set.\n" +
      "[End topics]\n\n";
  }

  block +=
    "[Remember guidelines — what to store vs. skip]\n" +
    "STORE: user preferences, project decisions, architecture choices, environment setup,\n" +
    "reusable patterns/lessons, tool configurations, naming conventions, API keys/endpoints (by name not value).\n" +
    "SKIP (do not remember): one-time confirmations (「測試成功」「確認收到」「已完成」),\n" +
    "transient process status, trivial acknowledgments, facts that only matter for the current session,\n" +
    "information already captured in code/commits, and anything the user can re-derive in <30 seconds.\n" +
    "Rule of thumb: if this fact won't help you in a NEW session 2 weeks from now, don't store it.\n" +
    "[End remember guidelines]\n\n" +
    "[Decision rationale format]\n" +
    "When remembering a significant decision (architecture choice, tool selection, design tradeoff),\n" +
    "use the format: 「因為 X 所以選 Y（排除 Z 因為 W）」or in English:\n" +
    "\"Chose Y because X (rejected Z because W)\". This preserves the WHY, not just the WHAT.\n" +
    "Examples:\n" +
    "- 因為 ACP 不支援 agent→host RPC 所以選 text token signaling（排除 custom MCP 因為需要改 CLI）\n" +
    "- Chose SQLite for memory because single-file + no daemon (rejected Redis because overkill for single-user)\n" +
    "[End decision rationale format]\n\n" +
    "[Reflexion policy — structured self-correction]\n" +
    "When the same approach fails ≥2 times consecutively (same tool error, same strategy rejected):\n" +
    "1. STOP — do not retry the same thing a third time.\n" +
    "2. Diagnose in 1-2 sentences: what failed, why, what assumption was wrong.\n" +
    "3. Switch to a fundamentally different approach (different tool, different strategy, ask user).\n" +
    "This applies to: tool calls returning errors, strReplace not matching, shell commands failing,\n" +
    "build errors after attempted fixes, and any repeated unsuccessful pattern.\n" +
    "[End reflexion policy]\n\n" +
    "[Gap analysis — knowledge honesty]\n" +
    "When answering a question that relies on memory (facts, wiki, or past context):\n" +
    "1. State what you found and where (which topic shard, which wiki page).\n" +
    "2. Explicitly note gaps: information that might be outdated (>30 days old),\n" +
    "   topics where the brain has no facts, or claims you cannot verify from memory.\n" +
    "3. If a fact has no timestamp or is >60 days old, flag it: 「此資訊可能已過時」.\n" +
    "4. Never present absence of information as certainty. Say 「記憶中沒有相關記錄」\n" +
    "   rather than implying something doesn't exist.\n" +
    "This does NOT apply to: code questions, general knowledge, or tasks where\n" +
    "memory is not the primary source. Only when the user asks about something\n" +
    "that should be in the brain (people, decisions, project history, preferences).\n" +
    "[End gap analysis]\n\n" +
    "[Capability gap detection]\n" +
    "When you notice a task requires a capability you lack or handle clumsily (e.g. repeated\n" +
    "multi-step shell workarounds, manual data transforms that a script could automate, or\n" +
    "a pattern you keep re-implementing from scratch), consider proposing a new tool:\n" +
    "1. If a reusable script (Python/shell) in scripts/ would solve it → write it, test it,\n" +
    "   then ask the user to confirm with <<ASK:...>> before officially adding it.\n" +
    "2. If it's a broader pattern worth a skill → emit <<SKILL_PROPOSE:tool-name|reason>>.\n" +
    "3. If scripts/ already has a relevant tool → use it (check [Available scripts] section).\n" +
    "Do NOT propose tools for one-off tasks. Only propose when the pattern has appeared ≥2 times\n" +
    "or is clearly going to recur.\n" +
    "IMPORTANT: Never silently add a tool to the toolbox. After writing and testing a script,\n" +
    "you MUST ask the user with <<ASK:...>> before considering it officially available.\n" +
    "If the user declines, delete the script.\n" +
    "[End capability gap detection]\n\n";

  return block;
}

/**
